                <note rend="inline" type="source">501.BB Palestine/7–2849</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Telephone Conversation, by the Deputy Under
                        Secretary of State</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Rusk</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-07-28">July 28,
                        1949</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I told Mr. Connelly<note n="1" xml:id="d865fn1">Matthew J. Connelly, Secretary to
                        President Truman.</note> that Ambassador Elath would probably bring up today
                    the question of retaining the arms embargo on Israel and the Arab States. I said
                    that Ralph Bunche had recommended to the Security Council that the various truce
                    resolutions be rescinded and that the Security Council proceed on the basis of
                    the armistice agreements. I told Mr. Connelly that the Secretary of State would
                    wish to discuss this matter very carefully with the President and that the
                    Secretary hopes that the President will make no commitment to Ambassador Elath
                    prior to the Secretary’s talk with the President.</p>
                <p>Mr. Connelly said that he would take care of the matter and see to it that the
                    President “just listens”. He stated that he would need nothing in writing, that
                    my telephone call was sufficient.</p>
            </div>
